column30:
Approaches to improve learning

 



Hiring Contract Teachers


In these programs, local instructors are recruited on a temporary contract, usually for one academic year. Their role is to support basic instruction in early grades (typically Grade 1–4) and to help reduce class sizes in overcrowded schools. These instructors may or may not have formal teacher training.



Providing Financial Incentives


In these programs, regular teachers are provided with financial incentives based on their students' test scores to encourage them to put more effort into supporting student learning. This means they receive a bonus if their students achieve better results in national tests.




How effective do you believe each of the following interventions is for improving student learning? - Hiring Contract Teachers

column48:
How would you like to allocate your USD 500, knowing that we might make a real donation on your behalf?




  

    
    
      Option A: Donation for Financial Incentives NGO
      
        This organization works to improve education quality by supporting teachers in underserved schools.
        By offering financial incentives based on student performance, it seeks to encourage effective teaching
        and improve student learning outcomes.
      

      
        The Impact of Financial Incentives on Learning:
        
          A scientific study evaluated a program that offered financial incentives to teachers based on their students’
          test score improvements.
        
        
          On average, students in schools where teachers received incentives scored about
          5 points higher (on a 100-point test) than students in schools without incentives.
        
        
          However, there is statistical uncertainty. Based on the data, the real difference could be anywhere between
          1 and 9 points.
        
      
    

    
    
      Option B: Donation for Contract Teachers NGO
      
        This organization works to improve education quality by recruiting and training contract teachers in
        underserved schools. By placing additional teachers in classrooms, it aims to reduce the workload of
        permanent teachers and provide more individualized attention to students.
      

      
        The Impact of Hiring Contract Teachers on Learning:
        
          A scientific study evaluated a program that placed locally hired contract teachers into classrooms to provide
          basic instruction and reduce class sizes.
        
        
          On average, students in schools with contract teachers scored about 3 points higher
          (on a 100-point test) than students in schools without contract teachers.
        
        
          However, there is statistical uncertainty. The real difference could be anywhere between
          2 and 4 points. - Option A: Donation for Financial Incentives NGO

How would you like to allocate your USD 500, knowing that we might make a real donation on your behalf?





Option A: Donation for Financial Incentives NGO

This organization works to improve education quality by supporting teachers in underserved schools. By offering financial incentives based on student performance, it aims to encourage effective teaching and improve student learning outcomes.


Financial Incentives – Evidence Summary

A scientific study evaluated a program that offered financial incentives to teachers based on their students’ test score improvements. On average, students in schools where teachers received incentives scored about 5 points higher (on a 100-point test) than students in schools without such incentives.

However, there is statistical uncertainty around this estimate. Based on the data, the real difference could be anywhere between 1 and 9 points.




Option B: Donation for Contract Teachers NGO

This organization works to improve education quality by recruiting and training contract teachers in underserved schools. By placing additional teachers in classrooms, it aims to reduce the workload of permanent teachers and support more individualized learning for students.


Contract Teachers – Evidence Summary

A scientific study evaluated a program that placed contract teachers—locally hired instructors on short-term contracts—into classrooms to reduce class sizes. On average, students in schools with contract teachers scored about 3 points higher (on a 100-point test) than students in schools without them.

However, there is statistical uncertainty around this estimate. Based on the data, the real difference could be anywhere between 2 and 4 points.





Below is a visual representation of the findings from both studies: - Option A: Donation for Financial Incentives NGO

column71: I chose to allocate the $500 with a greater share going toFinancial Incentives NGO and a smaller portion to the Contract Teachers NGO because my decision was driven by risk-adjusted impact, not just headline results. While hiring contract teachers shows a higher average improvement in test scores, the evidence also indicates a wide range of possible outcomes, suggesting that its success depends heavily on context and implementation. That level of variability introduces meaningful uncertainty when making a real donation on someone’s behalf. In contrast, financial incentives for teachers produce more modest gains, but those gains are consistently observed across settings, with a much narrower uncertainty range. This makes the intervention more predictable and easier to defend from an evidence-based standpoint. By weighting my donation toward the more reliable program while still supporting the higher-upside but riskier option, I aimed to balance impact with accountability, ensuring that the majority of funds are likely to generate measurable benefits while still allowing room for potentially larger gains. This choice reflects a cautious, evidence-driven approach that prioritizes reliability, credibility, and responsible decision-making under uncertainty.

Why I favored Option A (Contract Teachers): This program has the highest average impact (+5 points) and the best "top-end" potential. If we want to make a real dent in learning poverty, we should lean toward the intervention that can produce a 9-point gain. It also addresses the practical need for more teachers in crowded classrooms.

Why I still gave to Option B (Financial Incentives): I included this because it is more "stable." Even its worst-case scenario (+2 points) is better than Option A’s worst case (+1 point). It’s a safe, consistent way to make sure the donation definitely helps.

column134: When it comes to these sorts of question, I consider myself an "even-steven" guy -- I think it's the fairest way to resolve them. That being said, if I had a bias, it would lean towards the contract teachers -- who might be more effective, versus financial incentives, which can lead to corruption, particularly in nations that have a well-documented history of it. As an example, I remember a county commissioner who traveled to Zimbabwe, to do some mission work there, and was warned to buy pencils, papers and similar learning materials directly, then give them to the students -- because the fear expressed to him was, leaving them up to local officials might lead to them being sold for cash. column134:
Here in Michigan, we have some experience putting a microscope on standardized test scores.  What we discovered was that when you tell teachers that scores on a particular test are extremely important, the teachers will "teach to the test".  This definitely improves test scores but has been shown to have little bearing on improvements in actual student life (and career) skills.  All it shows is that teaching to the test will improve test scores.  Interestingly, that was an important piece of information, because the purveyors of the SAT and ACT have all along been insisting that this is impossible, despite a growing industry of for profit corporations providing SAT or ACT coaching for the purposes of helping get into "better" colleges.

I think that just throwing money at contract teachers no doubt has its own problems, but I personally have a little bit of experience there as well.  I have been a software developer for most of my career, but I took 2 years off and worked as a paraprofessional, split between 2 middle school band programs.  I had no academic background in music, but I could see that simply having an extra pair of hands in the classroom to deal with discipline issues, or to provide very basic instruction and positive reinforcement made a huge difference in kids' progress with their instruments.

Supporting Different Strengths: You are supporting two different ways to help students. Option A focuses on motivating existing professional teachers to improve their results, while Option B focuses on adding more people to the classroom to give kids personal attention.

Balancing Scientific Results: Even though the study for financial incentives showed a slightly higher gain (5 points) compared to contract teachers (3 points), you may feel that both results are positive enough to deserve funding.

Managing Uncertainty: Since learning environments are complex, you might feel it is safer to invest in two different strategies rather than putting all your money into just one, just in case one method works better in some schools than others.

Addressing Multiple Needs: You are helping to solve two separate issues: the need for better teaching effort (incentives) and the need for smaller class sizes (contract teachers).
